2.1 Primary Personas
Persona 1 — The Overwhelmed Professional
Profile:

25–45 years old

Works in tech, marketing, consulting, or operations

Has 2–5 inboxes (work + personal + side projects)

Receives 200–500 emails/day

Inbox unread count: 2,000–20,000

Pain Points:

Constant anxiety from unread count

Fear of missing important emails

Avoidance → inbox gets worse

Feels guilty for not staying on top of email

Email feels like a second job

Emotional Triggers:

Relief

Control

Progress

Clean slate feeling

Desired Feelings:

“I’m finally on top of things.”

“I’m not drowning anymore.”

“I can breathe again.”

Why They Use the Product:

Fast cleanup

Emotional payoff

Undo safety

AI suggestions reduce decision fatigue

Persona 2 — The Productivity Maximalist
Profile:

18–40 years old

Obsessed with optimization

Uses Notion, Superhuman, Arc, Raycast

Watches Ali Abdaal, Thomas Frank, Matt D’Avella

Inbox unread count: 0–200 (but hates clutter)

Pain Points:

Wants efficiency

Wants automation

Wants to feel “elite”

Wants tools that feel premium

Emotional Triggers:

Mastery

Speed

Flow state

Gamification

Desired Feelings:

“I’m operating at peak performance.”

“This tool makes me faster.”

Why They Use the Product:

Swipe speed

Combo streaks

AI insights

Automation rules

Persona 3 — The Casual User
Profile:

20–60 years old

Uses Gmail or iCloud

Doesn’t care about productivity

Just wants less clutter

Inbox unread count: 500–5,000

Pain Points:

Too many newsletters

Too many promotions

Doesn’t know how to unsubscribe

Doesn’t want to think about email

Emotional Triggers:

Simplicity

Ease

Fun

Visual clarity

Desired Feelings:

“This is easy.”

“This is fun.”

“I don’t have to think.”

Why They Use the Product:

Swipe simplicity

Visual feedback

No learning curve

Persona 4 — The Privacy‑Conscious Minimalist
Profile:

25–55 years old

Tech‑savvy

Uses Fastmail, ProtonMail, or IMAP

Avoids tools that read email content

Inbox unread count: 0–500

Pain Points:

Doesn’t trust AI that reads content

Wants transparency

Wants control

Wants minimalism

Emotional Triggers:

Safety

Transparency

Control

Clean design

Desired Feelings:

“My data is safe.”

“I know exactly what’s happening.”

Why They Use the Product:

Metadata‑only AI

Undo everywhere

No auto‑actions

Minimal UI

2.2 Deep Psychological Drivers
Driver 1 — Avoidance Relief
Email clutter creates avoidance loops:

The inbox grows → user avoids it → inbox grows more → shame increases

The product breaks this loop by:

Reducing decisions to a single swipe

Providing instant progress

Making cleanup feel fun

Driver 2 — Dopamine Through Motion
Humans respond strongly to:

Swipe gestures

Color changes

Haptic feedback

Sound cues

Progress bars

Combo streaks

This creates a micro‑dopamine loop:
Swipe → Feedback → Reward → Next swipe

Driver 3 — Control & Safety
Users fear:

Deleting something important

Breaking something

Losing access

Making irreversible mistakes

We counter this with:

Undo everywhere

Clear action previews

No auto‑actions

Transparent AI

Driver 4 — Clean Slate Psychology
A clean inbox creates:

Relief

Calm

Focus

Motivation

A sense of renewal

This is why the Victory Screen is essential.

Driver 5 — Progress Addiction
People love:

Streaks

Combos

Levels

Badges

Stats

These create a habit loop:
Progress → Satisfaction → Return

2.3 Pain Points Across Personas
Pain Point	Description	Product Solution
Too many emails	Overwhelming volume	Swipe cleanup
Hard to unsubscribe	Hidden links	Swipe right → auto‑unsubscribe
Spam keeps returning	Persistent offenders	Block + domain nuke
Fear of deleting important emails	Anxiety	Undo everywhere
No time to clean	Takes hours	100 emails in 2 minutes
Boring cleanup	No emotional reward	Gamification + motion
Lack of control	AI tools feel intrusive	Assistive AI only
2.4 Desired Emotional Outcomes
Emotion	How the product delivers it
Relief	Rapid cleanup + victory screen
Control	Clear actions + undo
Satisfaction	Motion + sound + combos
Mastery	Streaks + stats
Calm	Minimal UI + clean design
Trust	Transparency + safety rules
2.5 The Dopamine Loop (Core Habit Loop)
Trigger:  
Inbox clutter → stress → avoidance

Action:  
Swipe card → instant action

Reward:

Color flash

Icon animation

Combo counter

Progress bar

Sound cue

Investment:

Streaks

Stats

Inbox health score

Return:  
User comes back tomorrow.
